Introduction and Summary Brief


Nowadays, the entire United States are facing the racial inequality of law. As we have the incarceration data collected by the Vera Institute, we are able to explore how the situation changed with time and whether the situation is getting better in recent year.


First, let us get a glimpse of the data set. To exclude the missing value and discover recent trends, we chose to study the data generated from 2010 to 2018.

library(tidyverse)
#please set your own dictory
raw_data <- read.csv("incarceration_trends_preded.csv") #We exclude some variables from downloaded file, so please use csv. file we provided
#here we only focus on the time peroid 2010-2018
new_data <- raw_data %>% filter(year>=2010) %>% filter(year<=2018)

We mainly focus on the jail population by race,jail admission,jail pretrial and their rates. Those indicators were calculated by different methods (they were mainly average daily number) and can show the situation of incarceration. As we can see from the summary table, the average white people jail population count from 2010 to 2018 was 114.7 (which was the highest among other races). Howvever, we should be careful about their population count which was 419996.56 and it was much lower than black population count. Therefore, we can see that black people had the highest jail rate which was 0.0099 (and the total jail rate was only 0.002). In addition, we also discovered the jail admission and pretrial rates were rising from 2010 to 2018, especially, they almost reached the historical highest values in 2018. Those are the reason why we should pay attention to racial inequality and rationality of the judiciary in U.S.

Expolartory Analysis


Here, we would like to share the answers to those question and analyze the trends behind them.


Which county had the highest total jail admissions rate from 2017-2018?

library(ggthemes)
tja <- new_data %>% filter(year>=2017)  %>% 
  group_by(county_name) %>%
  summarise(
    Totaladmissions=mean(total_jail_adm_rate,na.rm=T),
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(Totaladmissions))
top10 <- tja[1:10,]

ggplot(top10) +
  geom_bar(aes(x= Totaladmissions,y = reorder(county_name, Totaladmissions)), width=0.5,stat='identity',fill="red") +
scale_y_discrete(position = "left")+
  theme_bw(base_line_size = 0) +
  labs(title= "TOP 10 county that had the highest average total jail admissions rate from 2017-2018",y = NULL,x="average value")


As seen in above figure, recent year those counties had highest average total jail admissions rates. This represents the number (rate) of times people are sent to prison from each county. Obviously, Dickens County should be more careful about putting people in prison and develop a robust system of law.


Which race had the highest total jail admissions rate from 2017-2018?

library(reshape2)
rjp <- new_data %>% filter(year==2018)  %>% 
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(
    Aapi=mean(aapi_jail_pop,na.rm=T),
    Black=mean(black_jail_pop,na.rm=T),
    Latinx=mean(latinx_jail_pop,na.rm=T),
    White=mean(white_jail_pop,na.rm=T),
    Total=mean(total_jail_pop,na.rm=T),
  ) %>%melt(                     
       id.vars=c("year"),  
       variable.name="Race",       
       value.name="rjp"             
       ) #long format

ggplot(rjp) +
  geom_bar(aes(x= reorder(Race,rjp),y = rjp), width=0.5,stat='identity',fill="blue") +
  theme_bw(base_line_size = 0) +
  labs(title= "Average jail population by race from 2017-2018",y = "Average jail population",x="Race and in Total")


As shown in picture, although average white people jail population count was the highest (which was round 150), we can not ignore that the white people population was also the highest. Therefore, there were still issues in inequity of Black and Latin people. (As their values were not much lower than white peoples values).


In previous study, we analyzed TOP 10 county that had the highest average total jail admissions rates from 2017-2018. Now we would like to know how the jail population by race changed from 2010 to 2018 in those county.

Rp <- new_data %>% filter(county_name=="Dickens County"|county_name=="Irwin County"|county_name=="Ziebach County"|county_name=="Brooks County"|county_name=="East Carroll Parish"|county_name=="Catahoula Parish")  %>% group_by(county_name,year) %>% summarise(
    AAPI=mean(aapi_jail_pop,na.rm=T),
    Black=mean(black_jail_pop,na.rm=T),
    Latinx=mean(latinx_jail_pop,na.rm=T),
    White=mean(white_jail_pop,na.rm=T)
) %>% melt(                      
       id.vars=c("county_name","year"),  
       variable.name="Race",         
       value.name="rjp"             
       )


ggplot(Rp) + geom_line(aes(x = year, y =rjp,color=Race))+ facet_wrap(~county_name)+
  theme_bw(base_line_size = 1) +
  labs(title= "Average jail population by race from 2010-2018 in (Top10 jail admission count)",y = "Average jail population",x="Year")


Apart from Dicken and Ziebach County, other counties had very unstable racial issues from 2010 to 2018. Especially, in Catahoula Parish the trends of Black and White jail population count were opposite during 2010 to 2018. Although, Dicken and Ziebach County had very stable line, they can ignore the fact that the jail population count varied by race from 2010 to 2018.


As for the variable comparison chart, we chose to study how average jail population, admission and pretrial rates changed from 2010 to 2018 in U.S..

Compare <- new_data %>% group_by(year) %>% summarise(
    jail_population_rate=median(total_jail_pop_rate,na.rm=T),
    jail_admission_rate=median(total_jail_adm_rate,na.rm=T),
    jail_pretrial_rate=median(total_jail_pretrial_rate,na.rm=T)) 

Compare1 <- Compare %>%melt(                      
       id.vars="year",  
       variable.name="Category",         
       value.name="Value"             
       ) #transform data to long format

ggplot(Compare1) + geom_line(aes(x = year, y =Value,color=Category))+
  theme_bw(base_line_size = 1) +
  labs(title= "Jail population, jail admission and jail pretrial rates changed from 2010 to 2018",y = "Rates",x="Year")


As we can see from above figure, the average jail admission rate were far more higher than jail population rates and jail pretrial rates from 2010 to 2018 (and its trends were unstable p.s. see following charts). This means that most jail admission were not successful and some of them were unnecessary. But we need to see trends and correlations among them. Therefore, we created following three line chart.

ggplot(Compare) + geom_line(aes(x = year, y =jail_population_rate),color="red")+
  theme_bw(base_line_size = 1) +
  labs(title= "Jail population rates changed from 2010 to 2018",y = "Rate",x="Year")

ggplot(Compare) + geom_line(aes(x = year, y =jail_pretrial_rate),color="blue")+
  theme_bw(base_line_size = 1) +
  labs(title= "Jail pretrial rate from 2010-2018 in Top10 jail admission county",y = "Rate",x="Year")

ggplot(Compare) + geom_line(aes(x = year, y =jail_admission_rate),color="darkgreen")+
  theme_bw(base_line_size = 1) +
  labs(title= "Jail admission rates changed from 2010 to 2018",y = "Rate",x="Year")


The trends of jail population rates and jail pretrial rate were almost the same from 2010 to 2018. And this is obvious and reasonable. However, the change of jail pretrial rates was less sensitive than jail population, which means that jail pretrial issue remains unsolved.


Now, we study the jail population count by race geographically. Through this kind of analysis, we could explore how they are distributed geographically and whether there were geographically correlations.


Firstly, we would like to discover the change of white people jail population count between 2010 and 2018.

library(usmap)
library(ggplot2)
#join dataset 2010
usdatawhite2010 <- new_data %>% filter(year==2010) %>% group_by(state,year) %>% summarise(
  white_jail_pop=mean(white_jail_pop,na.rm=T)
  ) %>% arrange(desc(white_jail_pop))
usdatawhite2010 <- usdatawhite2010[1:10,]
#join dataset 2018
usdatawhite2018 <- new_data %>% filter(year==2018) %>% group_by(state,year) %>% summarise(
  white_jail_pop=mean(white_jail_pop,na.rm=T)
  ) %>% arrange(desc(white_jail_pop))
usdatawhite2018 <- usdatawhite2018[1:10,]
#2010 map
usmapdata <-statepop
us2010 <- merge(usmapdata, usdatawhite2010, by.x = "abbr", by.y = "state",all.x=TRUE)
us2010[is.na(us2010)] <- 0
plot_usmap(
    data = us2010, values = "white_jail_pop", color = "red") + 
  scale_fill_continuous(
    low = "white", high = "red", name = "White people jail Population count (2010)", label = scales::comma
  ) + 
  labs(title = "US Map", subtitle = "These are the top10 states that had highest white people jail population count in 2010") +
  theme(legend.position = "right")

us2018 <- merge(usmapdata, usdatawhite2018, by.x = "abbr", by.y = "state",all.x=TRUE)
us2018[is.na(us2018)] <- 0
plot_usmap(
    data = us2018, values = "white_jail_pop", color = "red") + 
  scale_fill_continuous(
    low = "white", high = "red", name = "White people jail Population (2018)", label = scales::comma
  ) + 
  labs(title = "US Map", subtitle = "These are the top10 states that had highest white people jail population count in 2018.") +
  theme(legend.position = "right")


As seen from above two figures,the white people jail population counts on national boundary were very high both in 2010 and 2018. In addition there is a tendency to shift to the central part of U.S..

usdatablack2018 <- new_data %>% filter(year==2010) %>% group_by(state,year) %>% summarise(
  black_jail_pop=mean(black_jail_pop,na.rm=T)
  ) %>% arrange(desc(black_jail_pop))

usdatablack2018 <- usdatablack2018[2:10,] #top is DC with 2786 we remove them
us2018 <- merge(usmapdata, usdatablack2018, by.x = "abbr", by.y = "state",all.x=TRUE)
us2018[is.na(us2018)] <- 0
plot_usmap(
    data = us2018, values = "black_jail_pop", color = "black") + 
  scale_fill_continuous(
    low = "white", high = "blue", name = "Black people jail Population (2010)", label = scales::comma
  ) + 
  labs(title = "US Map", subtitle = "These are the top10 states that had highest black people jail population count in 2010.") +
  theme(legend.position = "right")

usdatablack2018 <- new_data %>% filter(year==2018) %>% group_by(state,year) %>% summarise(
  black_jail_pop=mean(black_jail_pop,na.rm=T)
  ) %>% arrange(desc(black_jail_pop))

usdatablack2018 <- usdatablack2018[2:10,] #top is DC with 1774 we remove it
us2018 <- merge(usmapdata, usdatablack2018, by.x = "abbr", by.y = "state",all.x=TRUE)
us2018[is.na(us2018)] <- 0
plot_usmap(
    data = us2018, values = "black_jail_pop", color = "black") + 
  scale_fill_continuous(
    low = "white", high = "blue", name = "Black people jail Population (2018)", label = scales::comma
  ) + 
  labs(title = "US Map", subtitle = "These are the top10 states that had highest black people jail population count in 2018.") +
  theme(legend.position = "right")


As shown in above two figures, top 10 states that had highest black people jail population count remains unchanged. Especially in Washington DC, the count of black people jail population even reached around 2700, the situation eased in 2018 (still much higher with 1774). Compared to white people, they were more concentrated in the east part of U.S., therefore, the local authorities in east part of U.S. are supposed to pay more attention to racial equality of the incarceration.
